metadata.name: Utopian Skyline #66
metadata.description:
Continuing the exploration of linear composition in the previous work, this work shows the utopian urban structure in an abstract form by using diagonal and non-uniform lines. To make this artwork more scattered and visually dynamic, just like musical notes that have to be interrupted somewhere, the lines are scattered and discontinuous using an animation algorithm. To see the artwork in detail, open it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Reaching #76
metadata.description:
Reach for the stars.

However impossible it may seem, there's always a way. As long as you believe.
Everybody has a way to their stars, and the only way to reach it is to try as hard as you can and believe in yourself. I will forever live by this and believe in it.

A couple of the palettes used in this piece were adapted from the ever great Studio Yorktown, thank you for providing these incredible combinations of colors :)

--

Press spacebar or right click to save an image.

--

Reaching is a piece I dedicate to my recently passed grandmother. Rest in piece, we love you and miss you.

metadata.name: Bear Prints #26
metadata.description:
The Bear was a patron of the arts while he was making LSD in California in the late 1960’s.  He had more acid money than he knew what to do with, and often commissioned major art projects while very, very high.  He always paid artists up front, and did not care how long the commissions took to complete.  Very many of these projects were abandoned or lost while The Bear was incarcerated in the early 70’s. 

This is an extended digital run of a lost series of psychedelic screen prints that were commissioned by the Bear.  The silkscreens and a few proofs were found in a storage unit in Oakland in the late 80’s.  20 years’ worth of rent had been paid up front, and the unit had not been opened since the fall of 1971.  The artist is unknown, but a contract in the Bear’s hand was found with the work, establishing provenance.

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #108
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: Block Storage #324
metadata.description:
VGAB::BLOCKS2/STORAGE

Generative Storage Blocks made with P5JS and random colors.

Save image as PNG with 's'.
Save image as JPG with 'S'.

Load 1x, 2x or 4x dimensions (2560 * 3840px) image with '1', '2' or '4'.

Remove / add white noise with 'n'.
Remove / add frames with 'f'.

** 4x pixelDensity tested only with Google Chrome **
** Blocks Series reserves always from the Block Office **

metadata.name: I AM UNFOLDING #44
metadata.description:
In the past, I was but fragments
Rough and jagged
Indefinitely, I weathered and grew
A sculpture formed, unstructured

In the present, I am the precipice
A grandiose monolith
My angles sharp, my lines precise
A work of art, restructured

The future looms before
A blank formlessness yet to be
My function undefined
In perpetuity, unfolding

-----------------------------------------

Best efforts have been made to optimize this project; however, for best performance, a machine with a dedicated GPU is recommended. Viewing the project in live mode is also recommended.

S - export a high resolution image.
P - pause the animation.
